  1. Now calculate population parameters: what is the mean thalach in the population. What proportion of patients have exercise induced angina (exang)?
summary_popn <- heart %>%
  summarise(
    mean_thalach = mean(thalach), 
    prop_exang = sum(exang == 1) / n()
  )

summary_popn
  • Mean thalach in the population: 149.6468647.
  • Proportion of patients with exercise induced angina (exang): 0.3267327.
  1. Now take a single sample of 50-patients from the population and calculate point estimates for mean thalach and proportion of exang from this sample (lets call these mean_thalach and prop_exang going forward).
    [Hint - use rep_sample_n() from the infer package to do this]
library(infer)

sample_50 <- heart %>%
  # ?rep_sample_n
  rep_sample_n(size = 50, reps = 1) %>% 
#  get rid of error '-' only defined for equally-sized data frames
  ungroup()

sample_50
summary_sample_50 <- sample_50 %>%
  summarise(
    mean_thalach = mean(thalach), 
    prop_exang = sum(exang == 1) / n()
   ) 

summary_sample_50
  1. What are the sampling errors of these point estimates?
    [Hint - remember a sampling error is defined as the difference between a point estimate drawn from a sample, and a population parameter]
# Sampling error = point estimate - population parameter
sampling_error = summary_sample_50 - summary_popn
sampling_error
  1. Now were going to repeatedly sample 50-patients from the population and build up sampling distributions for the mean_thalach and prop_exang point estimates. Take 5000 samples and store the sampling distributions in a variable rep_sample_50.
    [Hint - again, use rep_sample_n() to do this.]
sample_50_5000 <- heart %>%
  rep_sample_n(size = 50, reps = 5000)

rep_sample_50 <- sample_50_5000 %>%
  summarise(
    mean_thalach = mean(thalach), 
    prop_exang = sum(exang == 1) / n()
   )

rep_sample_50
  1. Visualise the sampling distributions of mean_thalach and prop_exang as histograms. How normal do the sampling distributions look?
rep_sample_50 %>%
